{"/service/ndnp/scu/batch_scu_icaco_ver02/data/sn82004649/00517016299/1908020601/0088.xml":{"full_text":"this we cannot knowingly assert, for our people\nthere have a noble and an honorable history.\nBut surely all will agree, and his people lovingly\nassert it, that Bro. Mitchell is a workman that\nneedeth not to be ashamed, and that in the few\nyears he has been there has accomplished a won\nderful amount of good.\nBro. Mitchell is a native of New York State.\nHe was engaged in a successful and lucrative\nbusiness from which he turned aside for the\nministry. He entered the Rochester Theological\nSeminary from which institution he graduated.\nHe was pastor in Nebraska, and at Niagara Falls,\nand Rhinebeck, N. Y. From Rhineheck he came\nto Camden. He was not a stranger in South\nCarolina when he was called to Camden, as he\nhad supplied the Johnston church for awhile. He\nhas attended several of our State Conventions\nand general meetings and has greatly endeared\nhimself to his brethren in South Carolina, who\nwill rejoice with him in his success.\nNext week we hope to give a picture of the\nnew church and of its beloved pastor. We\ngreatly enjoyed our visit to Camden and we re\ngret that the stay was too short to enable us to\nsee something of the work being done at the\nother Baptist church of which Bro. W. S. Wal\nters is pastor. This church is not far from the\nmill towns and we heard excellent reports of it.\nThey have a neat, attractive house of worship\nwhich cost two thousand dollars.\nDuring our stay in Camden we were in the\ncharming home of Mrs. DeJersey, which is also\nthe home of Deacon W. R. Eve, Jr. This greatly\nadded to our happiness and comfort. We had\nthe pleasure of being in the very delightful home\nof Bro. E. J. Lewis, who was very happy to en\ntertain Dr. Bailey and to be entertained by him,\nfor the Doctor was well, and in the best of\nspirits, and greatly enjoyed the dedication ser\nvice. He has assisted in 171 dedicatory services\nduring his twenty-two years\u2019 work in South Caro\nlina.\nEDUCATIONAL CAMPAIGN NOTES.\nRev. J. H. Edwards of Ridge Spring, writes:\n\u201cI will do what I can in bringing this most im\nportant campaign to a successful issue. We have\narranged for a special pastors\u2019 conference at my\nhouse next Monday in the interest of the cam\npaign.\u201d\nBennettsvilie reports over two thousand dol\nlars in five days, and the Pee Dee section will\nreach their full apportionments. A letter from\nthat goodly land says: \u201cI am confident that we\ncan succeed.\u201d\nDr. J. D. Pitts writes from Blackville: \u201cI be\nlieve with all my heart that Christian education\n(male and female) is at present thk work above\nall others for South Carolina Baptists, and I will\ndo what I can to make the movement a success\nhere.\u201d\nA Very Good Letter.\nHere is a good letter from a brother who evi\ndently read the suggestion that February be\nRenewal Month for all subscribers of The Courier\nwho are in arrears. We appreciate the prompt\nresponse and the very kindly expressions accom\npanying the remittance:\nLaurens, S. C., Feb. 3, 1908.\nBaptist Courier, Greenville, S. C.\nGentlemen: Find money order enclosed for\nfour dollars for subscription from Feb. 1, 1907,\nto Feb. 1. 1909. I want to say that I appreciate\nyour kindness in sending the paper right on to\nme while I was in arrears. Hope I will not get\nbehind again. Wishing you great success this\nyear, 1 am, C. C. Johnson.\nA DEADLY THING.\nA word frequently employed in the Book of\nActs to describe the attitude of the Jews to\nwards Peter, John, Paul and other early Chris\ntians, is jealousy. There are few things more\nnoxious, either on the earth, in the seas or flying\nthrough malarial regions. There is no passion\nof madness which has a vision more distorted or\na fury more unreasonable.\nAnd jealousy has an evil effect upon the per\nson in whom it is. Look at the fifth chapter of\nActs and see how it produced in the Jews hatred,\ndisappointment, perplexity and fear. Nobalm\ncan assuage its sting, and only death can heal its\nwound. It is a self-consuming fire, a self\ninflicted torment, an arrow that flies back and\nwounds the archer.\nSuspicion is the child of guilt: he who is al\nready corrupt is naturally suspicious. It is vain\nand foolish to imagine that the world is conspir\ning against you or has designs upon your suc\ncess. The truth is, probably, no one is even\nthinking of you. You are making yourself un\nhappy, magnifying every little circumstance,\nhowever trivial, in accordance with your own\nbiased vision.\nThe thing produces stagnation to development\nof character, and death. Jealousy\u2019s deepest\nwounds are made in the soul of the jealous per\nson.\nThe deadly thing can be eradicated. Strive\nagainst such an unfortunate disposition, and\nseek divine help to overcome it.\nPERSONAL AND EDITORIAL.\nFall in line with those who are making Febru\nary Renewal Month and send in a sum sufficient\nto pay all back dues and one year ahead.\nBro. W. A. Gyles, of Blackville, renews and\nsays: \u201cThis is my 33d subscription to Working\nChristian and Baptist Courier.\u201d We greatly\nvalue such a friend as Mr. Gyles.\nW. E. Huff, Seneca, says: \"My work is mov\ning along nicely. Have the same field that I\nhad last year, namely: Jordania, Mt. Tabor,\nMullens, New Hope, Hephzibah, Cross Roads and\nPoplar Springs.\u201d\nDr. J. S. Dill, pastor at Bowling Green, Ky.,\nis arranging to publish a brief biography of Dr.\nI. T. Tichenor, for so many years corresponding\nsecretary of the Home Mission Board. Dr. Dill\nis a son-in-law of Dr. Tichenor.\nOver twenty new students have entered the\nSeminary for the present half session. Many\nother pastors might do well to take a leave of\nabsence and spend several months in the Semi\nnary, and their churches could not render a\ngreater service and kindness than to make this\npossible by granting the vacation and furnishing\nthe means.\nThe building of the First church, Columbia,\nwas slightly damaged by fire Sunday morning.\nThe fire originated in the basement and was\ncaused by a flue of the heater, and damaged the\nbuilding about $400, fully covered by insurance.\nNo services were held Sunday, but the damage\nwill be repaired and the usual services will be\nheld next Sunday.\nThis statement from the Home Board ought to\nreceive the prayerful consideration of pastors\nand churches: \"Our contributions for home\nmissions during December, 1907, were only a\nlittle more than half what they were for Decem\nber, 190G. As we go to press the contributions\nfor January are much less than they were for\nthis period last year. We know that the financial\npanic will be given as an explanation of this\nserious falling off in our receipts. But that does\nnot relieve our situation, which has become\nacute. We beg our brethren everywere to come\nto our relief. Unless they, do, we shall not be\nable to borrow money to pay our workers their\nsalaries, to say nothing of pushing the great\nwork of church building in New Orleans, El Paso\nand scores of places.\u201d\nLisbon J. Allen, a student of the Freshman\nclass of Furman University, died of pneumonia\nafter a brief illness Tuesday morning, the 4th\ninstant. He was a member of the Latta Baptist\nchurch, and a son of Mr. E. C. Allen of Latta,\nS. C. The students of the University accom\npanied the body in procession to the train, and\nrepresentatives of the University attended the\nfuneral at Latta.\nThe Christian Index says: \u201cRev. M. L. Law\nson has changed his address from Henderson\nville, N. C., to Johnston, S. C. We are not in\nformed as to his plans. It will be remembered\nthat Bro. Lawson was pastor at Beaufort, S. C.,\nfor some years, where he did good work.\u201d We\nbeg to remind our brethren of the Index that\nBro. Lawson is now the beloved pastor of the\nJohnston Baptist church, where he is doing a\ngood work. Several years ago Bro. Lawson was\ncalled to this church, but at that time could not\nsee his way clear to accept the call.\nBrother J. Earle Freeman writes: \u201cOur Sun\nday School Field Secretary, Rev. J. D. Moore,\nwas with me at both of my churches Sunday,\nFebruary 2. At Rocky Creek he assisted in the\nordination of Brethren W. E. Powell, W. L. Bol\nton, L. I. Eidson as deacons, and also made a\nstimulating address on Sunday school work. At\na special service arranged for him at Dry Creek,\nhe also addressed the Sunday school in the after\nnoon, and we feel that good will come of his visit\nto' us, and will wish for his return. The above\nnamed churches take me for all my time this\nyear. Rev. Jabes Ferris takes the Ward church,\nand his many friends will be glad to learn that\nhe has recovered from a long illness, and is again\nable to enter the pastorate.\u201d\nThe city of Anderson is moving for a college\nfor women. A large and enthusiastic meeting\nwas held last week and it was decided to enter\nupon a canvass for funds. A large and repre\nsentative committee was appointed for this pur\npose. Professor W. S. Peterson, of Orangeburg,\nwas present and addressed the meeting, and en\ncouraged the citizens to undertake to raise fifty\nor sixty thousand dollars with which to begin\noperations. A number of addresses were made\nand the general sentiment was is favor of the\nproposition. Anderson is a live, growing, and\nprogressive city, and usually its people succeed\nm anything they undertake. There is no reason\nwhy they should not have a college that will be\na credit to the city and a blessing not only to\nAnderson and Anderson county, but to the State.\nWe wish them success\nDr. W. W. Hamilton, evangelist of the Home\nBoard, makes the following suggestions in the\nHome Field as to house-to-house visitation before\na meeting has commenced: (1) Divide the terri\ntory into districts. (2) Assign each church a\ndistrict, or if only one church, give to each com\nmittee a section. (3) Have committees assigned\nto each division of the district, and do not let\nthe division be too large. (4) Have all the com\nmittees meet at the church (or a half hour of\nconference and prayer. (5) Go out from this\nmeeting to the work two and two. (6) Have\nprinted blanks for information and pencils all\nready. (7) Have an invitation card and some\nliterature to leave in the homes. (8) Have a\ngood committee to tabulate information gained.\n(9) Give to pastor, \u00a7unday school superinten\ndent, ladies\u2019 society, teachers and others the in\nformation for each. (10) Follow up by letters\nand by visits those whose names have been se\ncured.","height":"17172","width":"12780"}}
